Dickens also illustrates Scrooge’s transformation by drawing parallels between his
attitude and the weather. At rst, when Scrooge is miserly and isolated, the weather is
“bleak” and “biting”. The word “biting” reects the impatient way he speaks to others, and the
alliterative ‘b’ puts emphasis on both words, highlighting the intensity of Scrooge’s miserable
demeanour. This contrasts starkly with his newfound joy in Chapter Five, which is illustrated
by the “clear” and “bright” weather. The word “clear” reects how his world view is no longer
clouded by misery, and “bright” implies that he is optimistic for the future. The association
between poor weather and unhappiness, and vice versa, is common in literature, so these
parallels encourage the reader to recognise Scrooge’s transformation as a positive one. The
connection between Scrooge and the weather could also reect how Scrooge no longer desires
to isolate himself from the world, as he now notices and delights in the joy he sees around him.
The circular structure of the novella illustrates the extent of Scrooge’s transformation,
as events are revisited in order to show how they have changed. In Chapter Five, Scrooge
encounters the charity collector that he previously argued with. While Scrooge left their
rst meeting only with an “improved opinion of himself”, he now worries how the man would
“look upon him”. This suggests that he has become more concerned about the effect his
behaviour has on others. Similarly, Bob Cratchit is initially referred to as “the clerk”: this
impersonal, business-like term shows Scrooge’s detachment from him. However, in the nal
scene, Scrooge calls Bob his “friend”. This shows how Scrooge’s attitude towards Bob has
changed, as he is now open to knowing him on a personal level. By revisiting scenarios from
the beginning of the novella, Dickens invites the reader to compare how Scrooge has changed.
This highlights his transformation and shows the reader how Scrooge is integrating into society.
Other characters also experience transformation within the novella. In the vision showing
the aftermath of Tiny Tim’s death, the Cratchits’ house is transformed from a place where they
“laughed tremendously” to somewhere “Quiet. Very quiet.” The short sentences bring the
narrative to an abrupt halt, emphasising how the Cratchits’ home has transformed from one
of happiness to one devastated by grief. However, as a result of Scrooge’s transformation, the
Cratchits’ lives are changed for the better and Tiny Tim survives, showing how one person’s
positive transformation can impact others.
Through the imagery, contrasting language and circular structure of the novella, Dickens
shows the extent of characters’ transformations. This makes the transformations all the more
vivid, and, through the character of Scrooge, suggests that even the most miserly of people
can change. By allowing the reader to experience the transformative power of the Christmas
spirit, Dickens hoped to change the attitudes of those who read the novella for the better.
